When to use Arrays.asList()

String[] arr = {"a", "b", "c"};
List<String> list = Arrays.asList(arr);
// list = ["a", "b", "c"]

Integer[] arr = {1,2,3};
List<Integer> list = Arrays.asList(arr);
-----

Not use with primitive arrays(int[], double[], etc)

int[] arr = {1,2,3};
List<int[]> list = Arrays.asList(arr);
// This is a List of one element: the int[] itself!
=> This gives a List<int[]> with one element, not a list of Integer
-------

âš ï¸ Limitations of Arrays.asList():
It returns a fixed-size list backed by the original array.

So you canâ€™t add or remove elements.

But you can modify existing elements.

java
Copy code
List<String> list = Arrays.asList("a", "b");
list.set(0, "z"); // OK
list.add("c");    // âŒ Throws UnsupportedOperationException
-------------------

âœ… Use Cases:
Goal	Should you use Arrays.asList()?
Convert String[] to List	âœ… Yes
Convert Integer[] to List	âœ… Yes
Convert int[] to List<Integer>	âŒ No â€” use loop or stream
Need a modifiable list	âŒ Wrap it: new ArrayList<>(...)
Just want to iterate, no changes	âœ… Yes
-------------------
ğŸ§  Tip:
If you need a modifiable list, wrap it:

java
Copy code
List<String> modifiable = new ArrayList<>(Arrays.asList("a", "b"));
modifiable.add("c");  // âœ… Works now


